<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Battle for Gorazde Continuing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Battle for Gorazde Continuing </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Attacks `Abated Somewhat' </H4>

<F P=102> AU0704091994 </F>
<F P=103> AU0704091994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Network in Serbo-Croatian at 0800 GMT on 7 April carries in its 
regular 8-minute newscast two reports on the current situation 
in Gorazde and Bihac. 
  Gorazde correspondent Enes Musovic reports that "after 
yesterday's extremely dramatic day, the aggressor's artillery 
fire and infantry attacks abated somewhat overnight. However, 
information from the farthest points of Gorazde's outskirts 
confirms that fierce fighting for the still free Gorazde is yet 
to come. The chetniks have been regrouping their forces all 
night in the areas of Peljin, Potkozara, Priselje, Trebinjaca, 
Postaja, and Rogatica. The aggressor is continuously bringing 
in fresh manpower and deadly weaponry. Over 350 mortars and 
howitzers, 46 tanks, and a supporting tank battalion already 
encircle Gorazde, while the aggressor, undisturbed, in full view 
of the international community, continues to kill and torture 
the civilian population in Gorazde, destroy residential and 
industrial areas, torch (?schools), destroy bridges." 
  Reporting from Bihac, correspondent Mirza Sadikovic says 
that 
"today marks the second month of the Serbian aggressor's 
fiercest offensive at the Bihac Commune. The offensive attacks, 
which began last night, continue this morning. Karadzic's 
terrorists used howitzers and tanks to shell Bihac [words 
indistinct]. They also intensified their artillery attacks at 
the defense lines on Grabez and the Grmusko-Srbljanski plateau." 
  "The attacks of the paramilitary forces of the so-called 
Kladusa autonomy at the outskirts of Cazin have been going on 
all night and have continued this morning. The autonomists are 
attacking Hadzici and the wider areas of (?Krivaja) and 
(?Tajici) with 60-mm and 80-mm mortars, armor-piercing weapons, 
and antiaircraft weapons, while infantry provocations have been 
reported on all the other demarcation lines. It is evident that 
the chetniks and the autonomists continue to coordinate their 
attacks [words indistinct] at the wider area of (?Osmaka) on the 
Buzim part of the front." 

</TEXT>

