<H3> <TI>   Serbian Women Blocking French UN Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian Women Blocking French UN Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0604154194 Paris AFP in English 1514 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0604154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 6 (AFP) -- A convoy of French UN 
peacekeepers has been held up for a week by around 100 Serb 
women in a village near Sarajevo, a spokesman for UN Protection 
Forces [UNPROFOR] said here Wednesday [6 April]. 
  The women who have blocked 34 military staff and 16 army 
vehicles since March 31 in the village of Hadzici are demanding 
the release of their husbands, held captive by mainly Moslem 
Bosnian government troops. 
  The convoy from the French Second Battalion was travelling 
from Sarajevo to Split when it was held up in Hadzici, 20 
kilometers (12 miles) west of the Bosnian capital. 
  "They are in constant contact with their unit, either in 
person or by radio, the situation is very calm and they are not 
at risk," Lieutenant Colonel Richard Pernod, spokesman for 
UNPROFOR in Sarajevo, told AFP. 
  Top-level negotiations to free the convoy were continuing 
Wednesday after a week of fruitless talks. 
  UNPROFOR civil affairs chief for former Yugoslavia Sergio 
Vieira de Mello tried to find a breakthrough Tuesday when he met 
Nikola Koljevic, deputy leader of the Bosnian Serbs, in the Serb 
headquarters at Pale near Sarajevo. 
  But Koljevic said the Pale authorities had no real control 
over Serbs in Hadzici, UNPROFOR spokesman Rob Annink said 
Wednesday, adding that Mello believed the convoy would be 
released soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

