<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDS Rally in Sofia Demands Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDS Rally in Sofia Demands Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504185894 Sofia BTA in English 1819 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 5 (BTA) -- A rally held in Sofia by 
the anti-communist Union of the Democratic Forces (SDS) today 
called on the cabinet to resign and demanded early elections. 
  Addressing the rally, SDS leader Filip Dimitrov said the 
union will use all parliamentary means to make the cabinet step 
down. He called upon the people to flood into the central 
square and remain there until the cabinet resigns in case the 
parliamentary means prove ineffective. The demonstrators 
chanted their approval. 
  "The Communists (the successor to the disbanded Bulgarian 
Communist Party is the Bulgarian Socialist Party) are ruling 
this country, pulling the strings of straw man Berov (the prime 
Minister)," said Ivan Kostov, MP of the SDS and former finance 
minister. "The choice is elections provoked by the SDS. Only 
the force that can bring about elections can be sure of winning 
them in this chaos," said Kostov. 
  SDS floor leader Stefan Savov said the SDS needed to poll 
not 
35 percent but 51 percent of the vote to form a strong 
government. The SDS scored a 34.6 percent victory at the 1991 
polls, which was not enough to form a stable cabinet. 
  The speakers charged the ethnic Turks' Movement for Rights 
and Freedoms and the New Union for Democracy with allying 
themselves with the Communists by backing the present 
government. President Zhelev was also accused of helping form 
the cabinet and supporting it so far. 
  For the first time at the rally, new songs written 
especially 
for the SDS election campaign were performed. The speakers 
called on people not to despair and go to the polls. 
  The rally chanted the name of exiled Bulgarian King Simeon 
and sang the old Bulgarian anthem (from the monarchy days) 
banned by the communist regime. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7883 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu067__a94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-067-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDS, BSP Consider Election Campaigns </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDS, BSP Consider Election Campaigns </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504135894 Sofia BTA in English 1423 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 5 (BTA) -- Bulgaria's major political 
forces, the anti-communist Union of the Democratic Forces (SDS) 
and former Communists' Bulgarian Socialist Party (BSP), are 
considering their election campaigns before elections are even 
scheduled. For more than a year the SDS have been calling on 
the cabinet of nonpartisan Professor Lyuben Berov to resign and 
insisting on early elections. Three days ago President Zhelyu 
Zhelev withdrew his support for the cabinet. The cabinet's 
resignation is a variant being considered by the ethnic Turks' 
Movement for Rights and Freedoms (DPS) on whose mandate the 
incumbent cabinet was formed in late December 1992. At a 
closed-door sitting late last week, the Socialists, for their 
part, decided to give a last chance to Prof. Berov's cabinet and 
granted them a month and a half to take under control the 
critical situation of the past couple of weeks. In the 
meantime, Prime Minister Berov, now recovering from a cardiac 
operation, publicized his plans about structural and personnel 
changes in the government. 
  The government has obviously come to an impasse, SDS leader 
Filip Dimitrov told journalists after a sitting of the union's 
supreme leadership. According to him, the government is trying 
very hard to convince people that the situation is improving. 
While the dollar seems to be under control, the prices do not. 
The statements of cabinet members sound most strange; they 
display a fake optimism and gross indifference to the man in the 
street, Filip Dimitrov went on to say. He reiterated the 
union's firm belief that the incumbent cabinet should step down. 
The SDS leader would not give further details as to the 
specific action the union is planning to take, adding only that 
it will resort to extraparliamentary means as soon as the 
parliamentary ones prove inefficient. 
  The SDS supreme leadership today also discussed its election 
campaign. This issue was high on the agenda of the BSP 
Executive Council. Socialists' leader Zhan Videnov told 
journalists that disbanding the parliament, which the effective 
constitution provides for in case a caretaker cabinet is 
appointed, is absurd when the country has embarked on the road 
of transition. Amendment of this provision in the constitution 
will require a majority of three quarters of the parliamentary 
votes. 
  Filip Dimitrov also said that the SDS leadership has not put 
for discussion the BSP proposal for amendment to the 
constitution to enable Parliament to sit even after the 
formation of a caretaker cabinet. According to the SDS leader, 
the fact that the Socialists are trying to launch the prolonged 
and complex parliamentary procedure for amending of the 
constitution comes to show that they are the ones who fear early 
election, not the SDS. The ex-Communists fear elections like 
hell, Filip Dimitrov also said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7884 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu067__a94003" </HT>


