<H3> <TI>   Papers Report Controversy Over Army Dismissals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papers Report Controversy Over Army Dismissals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504091694 Sofia BTA in English 0833 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From BTA's 5 April "Press Review"] </F>
  [Excerpt] Sofia, April 5 (BTA) -- "Army Threatens To 
Revolt Against Purge", DUMA writes on its front page. Defence 
Minister Valentin Aleksandrov is expected to dismiss some 3,000 
officers and 1,000 sergeants. According to DUMA, that might 
provoke unrest and even a revolt in the army. According to 
TRUD, 3,400 officers and twice as many sergeants will be sacked. 
"I have dismissed 200 and I will dismiss more," Defence 
Minister Aleksandrov reportedly said at yesterday's meeting of 
the National Security Council with the Presidency, writes DUMA. 
The minister explained that cuts were inevitable because of the 
inadequate budget. Participants in yesterday's [4 April] 
meeting suggested that an official declaration be issued for the 
press to prevent dismal rumours from spreading in the Army, but 
the head of the president's office, Mr. Ivaylo Trifonov, chose 
to make a routine and colourless statement, DUMA comments. The 
daily points out that the Bulgarian Socialist Party (BSP, the 
former Communists) opposed any "shock measures" before the 
coming into force of the Defence Act. 24 CHASA also writes that 
BSP leader Zhan Videnov was against the dismissals. A signed 
commentary in TRUD analyzes the current situation in Bulgaria 
and concludes that a Pinochet-type dictator might fit quite well 
in this country. STANDART NEWS reports that the council 
discussed the financial and currency crisis. "Politicians and 
the president fell out over the foreign debt," it comments. It 
also maintains that Deputy Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev and 
BSP floor leader Nora Ananieva angrily left the session long 
before it was over. "The foreign debt issue is not to be 
settled at the Presidency; there is a government for that, and 
we are no presidential state," said Ms. Ananieva. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

