<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Talks on Senatorial Elections Fail </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coalition Talks on Senatorial Elections Fail </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504192694 Prague CTK in English 1832 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 5 (CTK) -- Government coalition party 
experts today failed to reach any compromise on senatorial 
elections and will probably not meet again, Radim Spacek from 
the Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA) told journalists. 
  He added it was now up to the coalition party leaderships to 
"define the ground" for further negotiations. 
  Senatorial elections will probably be held along with 
communal elections in the autumn. The 81-seat Senate, in which 
one-third of the deputies will be elected every two years, is 
defined in the Czech Constitution but has not been created yet. 
  The coalition parties are split over the method of electing 
the senators. The strongest party, the Civic Democratic Party 
(ODS) of Premier Vaclav Klaus insists on 81 one-mandate 
constituencies, a proposal criticized by the other coalition 
parties -- the Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak People's 
Party (KDU-CSL), the ODA, and the Christian Democratic Party 
(KDS) -- which say the ODS wants to ensure for itself dominance 
of the Senate. 
  They propose the creation of 27 three-mandate 
constituencies. 
  The opposition parties are opposed to the Senate's very 
existence. 
  Spacek said that ODS representatives "will discuss any 
variant of senatorial elections as long as talks are about 81 
constituencies." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

