<H3> <TI>   Klaus Explains Settlement Plan for Russian Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Explains Settlement Plan for Russian Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0604071294 Prague CTK in English 1912 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0604071294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 5 (CTK) -- Agreement on the final 
date of signing a document on repaying the Russian debt means 
that several- year talks on the issue are drawing to a close, 
Premier Vaclav Klaus said after return from a two-day trip to 
Russia today. 
  The date is May 30. A "check date," May 15, was agreed upon 
in the talks with Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, Klaus 
said, adding that in case of problems the two premiers would 
speak over the phone on May 16 in order to remove the obstacles. 
  The agreement does not mean that the Russian debt, worth 
some 
$3.4 billion, will be paid back "starting tomorrow or the day 
after tomorrow," Klaus noted. "The agreement means a written 
acknowledgement of the debt and establishment of clear relations 
and clear schedule of the payments," he added. 
  The debt will be partly repaid on the basis of the 
principles 
of the "Paris Club of creditors," the rest by deliveries of 
goods and through Czech participation in Russian privatization. 
  Klaus admitted that the Czech Republic had been striving for 
collecting the debt by other means than through the Paris club 
which comprises economically advanced countries. 
  "We had hoped for a long time that we would be able to find 
other ways of payment, not being viewed as the rich West to 
which payments are made belatedly. I have to admit these dreams 
were unrealistic," Klaus said. 
  Klaus said he had not discussed security issues with 
President Boris Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

