<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Issues Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Issues Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504182694 Budapest MTI in English 1622 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 5 April (MTI) -- As reported earlier, 
audience protests disrupted Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza 
Jeszenszky's speech to a World War II Jewish Holocaust 
conference today. Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky's speech, to 
a conference on the Hungarian Holocaust at the Budapest 
University of Arts and Sciences, was drowned out by stamping and 
slow handclapping from audience members when he drew a parallel 
between Communism and Nazism. 
  A statement sent to MTI by the Hungarian Foreign Ministry 
today says Jeszenszky originally did not plan to contribute to 
the conference. However, he changed his mind when inspired by 
formal greetings, first of all by those of Chief Rabbi Jozsef 
Schweitzer, who expressed the hope that the conference would 
help people become familiar with justice and promote spiritual 
reconciliation. 
  Moved to contribute, Jeszenszky said he was pleased to 
realize that he could identify himself with the overwhelming 
majority of views expounded in the opening speeches. 
  Jeszenszky said it was Nazism that made it possible for 
Bolshevism to gain ground in Hungary. It cannot be forgotten 
that the liberation of Hungary in 1945 marked the beginning of 
another, decades-long dictatorship, he said. The minister 
quoted late prime minister Jozsef Antall as saying that both 
Nazism and Communism are barbarous ideas which should be 
condemned together. 
  At that point, some people in a corner of the hall started 
handclapping -- to prevent the minister from ending his speech 
rather than express their approval of his ideas, the statement 
says. 

</TEXT>

