<H3> <TI>   Goods Transport Protocol Signed With Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Goods Transport Protocol Signed With Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504162094 Budapest MTI in English 1412 GMT 5 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0504162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 5 April (MTI) -- This year's goods 
transport protocol was signed in Budapest today by Hungarian 
Minister of International Economic Relations Bela Kadar and his 
Ukrainian counterpart Oleh Slyepichev. 
  The ministers told the press that two-way trade was 
developing dynamically, despite a fall in production and export 
in both countries. Last year the trade turnover totalled $300 
million, of which Hungarian export amounted to $159 million, and 
import to $141 million. Ukraine is the 14th biggest trade 
partner of Hungary. 
  Kadar and Slyepichev said the organizational framework for 
bilateral links had been established. To date, about 300 
Hungarian- Ukrainian joint ventures have been set up. In a move 
to promote their operation, the two countries are likely to sign 
an investment protection agreement soon. 
  The two ministers voiced their wish to strengthen 
cooperation 
between Hungary, Ukraine, and Slovakia, and said the three 
states will seek help from the European Bank for Reconstruction 
and Development to finance projects in the region. 
  The Ukrainian minister thanked Hungary for a $1 million loan 
for the reconstruction of the Beregszasz hospital. The loan is 
to be repaid through goods deliveries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7907 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu067__a94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-067-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

