<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Denies Sending Weapons to Iran </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Denies Sending Weapons to Iran </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704064994 Prague CTK in English 1636 GMT 6 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704064994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 6 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic is not 
presently exporting any weapons to Iran, Ilja Mazanek, director 
of the Foreign Ministry's Middle Eastern and North African 
Department told CTK today. 
  If the ministry ever does grant an export license for 
weapons 
shipments to Iran, it will only be in accord with international 
interests, according to international agreements, and following 
a tough licensing process, Mazanek said. 
  He emphasized that no UN sanctions were currently in place 
against Iran as there were against Libya and Iraq, but that Iran 
nevertheless was considered a "sensitive" area, and consequently 
weapons deliveries that could be "problematic" would not be 
condoned. Such deliveries included not only weapons, but 
components for nuclear power plants. 
  Mazanek said that so far no firm had applied for a license 
to 
export parts to Iran for Warsaw Pact-model tanks which had been 
delivered to Iran in the past. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

