<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Reveals Negative Opinions on Walesa's Work </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Reveals Negative Opinions on Walesa's Work </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604190694 Warsaw PAP in English 1726 GMT 6 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0604190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 6 -- Seventy per cent of respondents 
to the "Demoskop" opinion polling centre survey sized up 
negatively the work of President Lech Walesa over the past few 
weeks. Eighteen per cent sized up Walesa's work in this period 
positively and only very positively. The remaining respondents 
did not express their opinion on this topic. 
  Forty-four per cent of the respondents sized up Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak's performance positively, 36 per cent 
-- negatively and two per cent respondents assessed it very 
positively and 18 per cent did not have an opinion on this topic. 
  Forty-three per cent of respondents gave negative opinion of 
the government performance over the past few weeks. Twenty-nine 
per cent offered positive opinion and 7 per cent of respondents 
had a very low opinion of the government work. Every fifth 
respondent did not express opinion on this topic. 
  According to 55 per cent of respondents to a poll by the 
Public Opinion Research Centre (CBOS), people ruling before 1989 
are now returning to government and ministerial posts. 
  In the opinion of 41 per cent of respondents, such persons 
return to provincial authorities. According to 34 per cent, 
these people return to posts in the management of state 
enterprises. 
  Thirty-three per cent think that people who ruled before 
1989 
are now returning to boards of banks. 

</TEXT>

