<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa, Finland's Haavisto Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa, Finland's Haavisto Hold Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604153394 Warsaw PAP in English 1525 GMT 6 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0604153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 6 -- President Lech Walesa received 
Finnish Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto on Wednesday afternoon, 
according to the presidential press office. 
  "As countries of medium size we should play a bigger role in 
Europe. Poland and Finland want to find themselves in European 
organisations which have shown themselves to be effective. 
Finland has already succeeded, Poland still faces a long road," 
Walesa said. 
  The talks also covered security. "The stationing of such a 
numerous (Russian) army in the Kaliningrad region is a worrying 
phenomenon. It is difficult to explain this phenomenon in 
peacetime. After speaking to many international politicians I 
have found that this problem is not enough known to world 
opinion," Walesa added. 
  He also drew attention to the insufficient aid given by the 
West to facilitate the changes taking place in east and central 
Europe. 
  Walesa stressed that these countries needed to be included 
in 
the world market economy, something which could not be done 
while thinking in old categories. Europe needed a new vision. 
If this did not take place then the lack of political and 
economic security in the region would adversely affect the rest 
of Europe. 
  Haavisto gave assurances that Finland would support Poland's 
efforts to join the European Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

