<H3> <TI>   Meciar: Coalition Trying To `Renew' CSFR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meciar: Coalition Trying To `Renew' CSFR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704095394 Prague CTK in English 2055 GMT 6 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0704095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 6 (CTK) -- Former Slovak Premier 
Vladimir Meciar today accused the chairmen of the Democratic 
Left Party (SDL) and of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH), 
Peter Weiss and Jan Carnogursky respectively, of attempts to 
renew the joint Czech-Slovak state. 
  Meciar was speaking at a meeting of his Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) which was marked with strong 
criticism of President Michal Kovac and especially of Jozef 
Moravcik's government. 
  Meciar said that "Peter Weiss is playing a big game going 
beyond the borders of his party, and this even at the cost of 
the SDL's disintegration," Meciar said referring to the 
unsuccessful talks between the HZDS and the SDL on the formation 
of a coalition government before Meciar's government fell on 
March 11. 
  Meciar claimed that during his meeting with President Bill 
Clinton last year, Carnogursky presented a three-point plan 
aimed at disintegration of the HZDS with the help of Milan 
Knazko (fired by Meciar from the post of foreign minister in 
March 1993), to be followed by the restoration of Czechoslovakia. 
  Meciar also said that present Premier Jozef Moravcik and 
Deputy Premier Roman Kovac "would have had to leave the 
government because they had made gross mistakes." Moravcik was 
foreign minister and Kovac held the same post as now. 
  Meciar today accused both of them of inactivity and of 
telling lies. "In the material which he had prepared for me 
before my trip to Rome, Moravcik called the Vatican the center 
of ideological subversion," Meciar said. 

</TEXT>

