<H3> <TI>   Carnogursky Backs `Loose Cooperation' of Right </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Carnogursky Backs `Loose Cooperation' of Right </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804084494 Prague CTK in English 1815 GMT 7 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 7 (CTK) -- The Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH) and the Democratic Party (DS) have 
discussed cooperation between the right-wing parties, KDH 
Chairman Jan Carnogursky told CTK today. 
  The KDH is for loose cooperation of all the parties right of 
the centre, in particular the DS (extra-parliamentary), the 
National Democratic Party-New Alternative and the Party of 
Entrepreneurs and Tradesmen, added Carnogursky, Slovak prime 
minister between 1991 and 1992. 
  The KDH has also established contacts with "Knazko's 
followers" and "Moravcik's followers" who want to create the 
Slovak Democratic Union on April 23. Milan Knazko is a former 
Slovak Foreign Minister who heads the Alliance of Slovak 
Democrats (AD SR). Josef Moravcik, current prime minister, 
recently created the Alternative of Political Realism (APR). 
  "National differences seem to be stronger than ideology," 
Carnogursky commented on contemplations of possible contacts 
with the ethnic Hungarian parties. 
  However, he did not rule out cooperation with them because 
"apart from some aspects of ethnic policy our views are very 
close." 
  "Bilateral meetings of the right-wing parties will continue 
and we would also like to stage a multilateral session this 
month," Carnogursky announced. 

</TEXT>

