<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Melescanu, Belgian Counterpart Discuss Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Melescanu, Belgian Counterpart Discuss Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704082794 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1900 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0704082794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Romanian Foreign Minister Teodor Melescanu and 
Willy Claes, deputy prime minister and foreign minister of 
Belgium, held official talks in Bucharest today on political 
relations between the two countries, economic relations, and 
possibilities of making use of judicial and parliamentary levers 
to stimulate commercial exchanges between the two countries. 
  According to our correspondent's report, the Belgian 
minister 
expressed the determination of his country to support Romania 
both in the PHARE [Economic Reconstruction Aid for Poland and 
Hungary] program as well as in the Group of 24. The two 
ministers also examined the possibility of facilitating trips of 
certain Romanian citizens to Belgium. 
  In a statement made at the end of talks, Claes said that the 
most important message that he brings to Romania is that the 
Group of 12 has no intention of promoting a discriminatory 
policy between Central European countries and that Romania is 
not a second-class Central European country. 
  As far as Romania's association with the European Union [EU] 
is concerned, Willy Claes said that the treaty of association 
should be regarded as a last step before the association, 
however, before 1996 no negotiations can begin on this issue 
because neither Romania nor the other Central and Eastern 
European countries are prepared for this stage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

