<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Accused of Violating UN Charter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Accused of Violating UN Charter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704153694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1317 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0704153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Pool report] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 7 (TANJUG) -- The North Atlantic 
Council ignores the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) plea 
to the International Court of Justice in The Hague against all 
NATO member-countries for resorting to ultimatum and threatening 
to use force in the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  TANJUG has learned from reliable sources that when the North 
Atlantic Council recently met at the level of permanent 
representatives it held a debate on the F.R.Y. plea for the 
Hague court to institute proceedings against the NATO 
member-countries for violating international law by resorting to 
ultimatum and the threat with the use of force. 
  The North Atlantic Council on February 9 threated to launch 
air strikes against Bosnian Serbs and Moslems unless they 
withdrew or placed under U.N. control their heavy weapons in and 
around Sarajevo within ten days. The ultimatum was interpreted 
in the West as applying only to the Bosnian Serb side. 
  TANJUG has learned from the same sources that a broader 
discussion about the F.R.Y. plea at the meeting of the North 
Atlantic Council was prevented by the U.S. representative, who 
insisted on his government's position that the F.R.Y. plea did 
not deserve a reply because it was politically motivated. The 
U.S. representative urged the NATO member-countries not to 
recognize the Hague court's jurisdiction in the case. 
  It is set out in NATO circles that the U.S. prevented a 
substantive debate and avoided a confrontation with the NATO 
member-countries, such as Greece, who had reservations when 
decisions concerning military operations in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
were being taken. 
  According to the available information, the International 
Court of Justice is still waiting for replies from the NATO 
member-countries whom it has asked in writing to let the court 
know whether they accept the court's jurisdiction in the 
respective case. 
  The F.R.Y. on February 18 filed the plea against the NATO 
member-countries. 
  The NATO ultimatum and threat to use force were gross 
violations of Articles 2 and 53 of the U.N. Charter. Article 2 
bans the threat with or use of force, and Article 53 enables 
certain measures to be taken but only on condition they are 
decided on by the U.N. Security Council. 
  It is well known that the U.N. Security Council had not 
taken 
a decision for the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw their heavy weapons 
in the Sarajevo area by February 20, and that U.N. 
Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali had asked NATO only to 
report to him about whether it was ready possibly to intervene. 
Neither the Security Council nor the secretary-general had 
authorized NATO to set ultimatums and threaten with the use of 
force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7966 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu068_y_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-068 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Discusses Finances, Foreign Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Discusses Finances, Foreign Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504192994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1808 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 5 April (TANJUG) -- According to a 
statement by the Federal Ministry of Information, at its 
session, chaired by Prime Minister Radoje Kontic, today the 
Federal Government examined and adopted the draft law on a 
foreign currency loan to be raised by the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia [FRY] both at home and abroad to the tune of $300 
million to finance its program of transforming monetary system 
and the strategy of the country's economic recovery. [passage 
omitted] 
  Under the draft law, the loan would be paid off over 
two-year 
period with a one-year grace period and at the interest rate and 
other terms as customary on the financial market. The loan will 
be repaid in 12 equal monthly installments and the loan 
repayment fund -- to equal the amount used up -- will be secured 
by the FRY, or rather the republics. [passage omitted] 
  At this evening's session the Federal Government considered 
and approved a document entitled: "FRY Government stances on the 
initiatives of other states to conclude agreements on friendship 
and cooperation." 
  Bearing in mind the changes which have taken place in 
Europe, 
globally and in the Balkans, as well as changes in the 
international position of the FRY, the Federal Government 
assesses that it is necessary to accept the initiatives of 
friendly, neighboring countries to conclude general agreements 
on friendship, good-neighborliness and cooperation in order to 
strengthen the country's international position and stimulate 
bilateral and multilateral cooperation. [passage omitted] 
  The government at the same time approved the Yugoslav draft 
text of an agreement on friendship and cooperation between the 
FRY and Romania, the Federal Information Ministry's statement 
says at the end. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

