<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Firemen Unable To Approach Blaze </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Firemen Unable To Approach Blaze </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804122994 Paris AFP in English 1132 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0804122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, April 8 (AFP) -- Giant flames licked a 
munitions dump in the Zagreb suburbs Friday [8 April] a day 
after massive explosions injured 17 people, and five others were 
still missing, authorities announced. The explosions stopped at 
1:00 a.m. (2300 GMT Thursday), 11 hours after the dump was 
rocked by a first blast. 
  Croatian Prime Minister Nikica Valentic, who Thursday 
announced an evacuation order for all residents within a 
2.5-kilometre (1.5-mile) radius, said the blasts in the depot in 
Sesvete, about 12 kilometres (seven miles) outside Zagreb, were 
a "disaster." 
  Deputy Defense Minister Josip Juras said he did not rule out 
sabotage. 
  Damage was huge but could not be immediately assessed. 
Firemen were still unable to get near the flames Friday at 
noon. Ten buildings near the military facility were destroyed 
by exploding ammunition and 100 others were damaged. 
  Fragments of exploding mortars and, according to western 
experts, probably of ground-to-ground and anti-tank missiles, 
flew around and even seriously injured a man in a central Zagreb 
street Thursday. Authorities maintained a general alert but 
traffic near the dump was reopened. 
  The numerous blasts opened up a huge crater at the dump 
which 
is one of Croatia's biggest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

