<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Sets Conditions for Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Sets Conditions for Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704224294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] 
reports concerning the possibility of a meeting between 
representatives of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the Serb 
aggressor side under the chairmanship of General Michael Rose, 
the press center of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army has been 
authorized to issue the following statement: 
  1. In order that talks on a general cease-fire between the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the Serb aggressor side can start it 
is vital that the Serb aggressor side immediately stop all 
offensive actions against the towns of Gorazde and Bihac, which 
have been proclaimed protected areas by the UN Security Council. 
  2. The Serb aggressor formations should return to their 
starting positions, which they held on 3 March this year when 
they launched an offensive against Gorazde. 
  3. In order that talks with representatives of the Serb 
aggressor side can begin it is necessary to have clearly defined 
political prerequisites which guarantee the continued political 
process of resolving the Bosnia-Herzegovina problem as a whole. 
  4. Representatives of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, led by 
Army General Rasim Delic, are ready at any time to have talks 
with representatives of the UNPROFOR and with other 
international organizations concerning the situation in Gorazde 
or in any other part of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Gen. Rose was told 
this during his talks today with Army Gen. Delic, the statement 
issued by the press center of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army reads. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

