<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Threatens Counteroffensive </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Threatens Counteroffensive </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0704144894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1401 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0704144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Trebinje, 7 April (TANJUG) -- Srpska republic 
President Radovan Karadzic said in Trebinje today that he was 
increasingly optimistic and hopeful of a speedy and peaceful 
solution to the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Karadzic bases his modest optimism on the fact that, as he 
said, the orientation toward peace has prevailed in the world 
and also because of the superiority of the Srpska army. 
  Karadzic added that the Muslim side would eventually have to 
sit at the negotiating table because it cannot achieve anything 
on the battlefield. 
  The international community is tired of the war and is 
afraid 
of a Balkan war, Karadzic said addressing journalists. 
  In connection with the situation in Gorazde, Karadzic said 
that the Serb side had earlier warned of the planned Muslim 
spring offensive, saying that it would respond with all 
available forces. 
  If the Muslims do not stop attacking, we will launch a 
counteroffensive and then let the Security Council save them, 
Karadzic said in Trebinje where he inaugurated the festival of 
Ducic's Evenings of Poetry. He was presented the festival's 
award. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

