<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Health Minister on Undernourishment, Epidemics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Health Minister on Undernourishment, Epidemics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0704201394 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0704201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Professor Mustafa Beganovic, health minister </F>
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, by Senada Cumurovic; place and date not 
given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Cumurovic] World Health Day and the 70th 
anniversary of the Health Protection Institute of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina are being marked this year under grave living 
conditions. Professor Beganovic, can you tell us about the 
health situation of the citizens of Bosnia-Herzegovina? 
  [Beganovic] This situation is rather grave. There is 
undernourishment. There are epidemics of infectious diseases, 
although they have not been widely spread, they have not grown 
into pandemics. For that, we can, above all, thank our people, 
who know how to maintain hygiene even under such conditions and 
also thank our medical staff who are making efforts and [words 
indistinct] to help people as much as possible. [passage 
omitted] 
  In this free part of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, we 
have about 70,000 seriously wounded people, a large number of 
disabled, a large number of paraplegics, a large number of cases 
of chronic diseases, a large number of cases of psychological 
disorders, and, generally speaking, we were very rarely able to 
help and do something for the improvement of health. We were 
trying to save lives, we were saving elementary health so a 
person would not die, would survive, and then, with time, we 
shall try to return him to full health. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

