<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister, Talbott Talk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister, Talbott Talk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104105094 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1000 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 11 Apr--A meeting between Prime Minister 
Waldemar Pawlak and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe 
Talbott lasted nearly one and a half hours. Talbott is paying a 
two-day official visit to Poland. 
  After the meeting, Pawlak told journalists that talks 
focused, among other things, on Polish-U.S. cooperation in 
international financial and economic organizations such as the 
World Bank, the IMF, and the OECD. Views were also exchanged on 
the "Partnership for Peace" [PFP] program. Pawlak announced 
that Polish-U.S. talks at the experts' level would be held soon. 
They should lead to joint undertakings this year within the 
framework of Poland's cooperation with NATO. 
  According to Pawlak, development of the whole 
Central-Eastern 
region of Europe was also discussed, as well as the possibility 
of U.S. support for the process. 
  Talbott said that the United States was of the opinion that 
Polish reforms were yielding good results. He stressed that the 
United States was the largest investor in Poland and that 
economic relations between both states might still be expanded. 
Talbott pointed out that economic issues would probably be the 
main subject of talks by President Bill Clinton during his visit 
to Poland in July. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

