<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   News Conference Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    News Conference Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004181494 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1004181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime ministers of Poland and the Czech Republic 
have met in Czocha Castle in the Jelenia Gora province near the 
frontier. 
  At a news conference following their informal meeting, 
Waldemar Pawlak and Vaclav Klaus described their talks as very 
concrete. They concerned, above all, economic cooperation, but 
not exclusively, because they also talked about European 
integration and the Polish minority in the Czech Republic. 
  It is not true that Polish-Czech relations are not good, 
declared Vaclav Klaus, and added that there was no other country 
whose politicians he was meeting as often. He recalled his 
talks with Waldemar Pawlak at the Visegrad-U.S. summit, with 
Aleksandr Kwasniewski in Davos, Sejm Speaker Jozef Oleksy's 
visit to Prague, and announced a meeting with President Lech 
Walesa next week. 
  Prime Ministers Pawlak and Klaus agreed, among other things, 
that the Polish debts would also be paid off through ecological 
investment projects. We would be most willing to provide coal, 
but the Czechs also have problems in this branch of the 
industry, and that is why the agreement finally was for ecology 
and a border infrastructure. 
  For Waldemar Pawlak, the most important matters in relations 
with the Czechs are agreements concerning the Central European 
Free Trade zone and border cooperation. 
  Vaclav Klaus appealed to Polish journalists not to put a 
political slant on the matter of reduced subsidies for Polish 
organizations active in the Czech Republic. The prime minister 
explained that his government had given up lump-sum subsidies in 
favor of supporting specific undertakings. Vaclav Klaus 
announced a financial shot in the arm for Polish minority 
organizations in the second half of the year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

