<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation After Rejection of Popiwek Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation After Rejection of Popiwek Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1104133994 Warsaw TRYBUNA in Polish 11 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS1104133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TRYBUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Stanislaw Cwik under the rubric "One Hundred </F>
Words"] 
  [Text] The Sejm and the president have prepared an 
unexpected experiment for the Polish economy. They decided that 
decisions concerning wages would be made by company directors, 
employees' councils, and trade unions. Thus, we partially 
returned to socialism. The prime minister must again appeal to 
work forces and to the responsibility of managers. 
  I believe that there are two solutions to this problem: 
first, returning to a new popiwek [tax on excessive wage 
increases] as soon as possible, and second, changing the system 
of most state-run enterprises, establishing a one-person 
Treasury partnership, and privatization. 
  The first method has proved itself. However, the fear of a 
new popiwek law may result in wage panic today, not to mention 
high inflation. The other method calls for some time. It may 
also encounter political resistance because not everyone in 
Poland supports privatization and modernization of oversized 
economic companies. 
  Each of these scenarios is to a certain extent risky. It 
seems, however, that safer is the "escape forward"--that is, 
acceleration of the pace of economic reforms. This calls for 
specific decisions already today. Also, the work forces of 
state-owned companies should be told what they will go through 
soon--for example, that there will be no popiwek, but there will 
be bankruptcies. Or that not only the rights of various sectors 
of our economy will be equalized, but also their duties toward 
the Treasury. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8039 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu069_p_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Kwasniewski Best Presidential Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll: Kwasniewski Best Presidential Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0804144694 Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA in Polish 8 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> WS0804144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by R.W.: "According to CBOS Respondents: </F>
Kwasniewski for President"] 
  [Text] A year and a half before presidential elections, 
Aleksander Kwasniewski [chairman of the Social Democracy of the 
Polish Republic] is the best candidate for next president of 
Poland. The Public Opinion Research Center [CBOS] conducted a 
survey at the end of March using a list of politicians, and 
Kwasniewski gained the highest support (17 percent). His 
"presidential popularity" has not changed since January. But 
there are clearly far fewer people (compared with the beginning 
of the year) who would be willing to support Lech Walesa or 
Krzysztof Skubiszewski in the race for the Belweder (or, as the 
case may be, to Namiestnikowski Palace). Apart from Kwasniewski, 
only [Prime Minister] Waldemar Pawlak managed to gain the 
"votes" of at least one in 10 prospective voters, during the 
March poll. Support for Zbigniew Religa, chief of the Non-Party 
Bloc in Support of Reforms, increased slightly since January; 
Religa now occupies third place on the list of presidential 
candidates. Respondents' views continue to be very diversified. 
Therefore, no one from among the personalities named by CBOS can 
regard himself as a definite favorite on the basis of the poll 
only. It is worth stressing that just 2 percent of respondents 
say Jacek Kuron, who leads in popularity polls, would make a 
good future president. No politician of the center right enjoys 
significant support. Respondents do not have anyone "in 
reserve," either. Just 7 percent of respondents said they would 
vote for somebody who is not on the CBOS list. The CBOS poll 
was conducted on 25-28 March (1,230-person representative random 
sample of the country's adult population) and 27-31 January 
(1,172-person sample). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
