<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UNPROFOR Denies Chemicals Used </H4>

<F P=102> LD1004144394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1407 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 10 (TANJUG) -- A representative of 
the U.N. Protection Force for former Yugoslavia (UNPROFOR) on 
Sunday denied claims by the Moslem leadership in Sarajevo that 
Serb forces had used poison gases and killed thousands of 
civilians in an attack on Gorazde, a Moslem enclave in eastern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Spokesman Rob Annink told reporters in Sarajevo that Serb 
forces had possibly only used smoke mortars in the region of 
Gorazde, the French news agency AFP said. 
  The Moslem presidency in Sarajevo said on Saturday evening 
that thousands of people had been killed in the Serb attack on 
Gorazde when poison gases were used. The statement was 
immediately carried by leading news agencies from all over the 
world. 
  Moslem Radio Sarajevo even said that the Gorazde suburbs of 
Bace and Mlinarice were pounded with chemical shells, with 
1,000-10,000 casualties as a result. 
  Moslem Presidency Vice-President Ejup Ganic said that he 
would leave for New York already on Sunday to ask for an 
emergency session of the Security Council because of this 
incident. 
  Deputy commander of the general staff of the Bosnian Serb 
army, General Milan Gvero on Sunday told TANJUG that the Serb 
side had never used chemical weapons in the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The Serb side does not manufacture, possess 
or use such weapons, he was adamant. 
  Gen. Gvero said that the Moslem side was using poison gases 
in order to accuse the Serbs and provoke a military intervention 
against them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8054 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu069_i_94006" </HT>


