<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Gorazde Being `Destroyed' </H4>

<F P=102> LD1004111294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1000 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1004111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fahrudin Becic from Gorazde] </F>
  [Text] Gorazde increasingly resembles a mass grave. Over 
100 dead and about 500 wounded are the consequence of the 
frenzied attacks by Karadzic's followers. Nothing is known 
about the fate of many people from the right bank of the Drina 
River. Many are believed to have been massacred and left among 
the charred remains of villages in the southern section of the 
battlefield. The battle hospital is caring for the wounded with 
superhuman efforts. There are no medicines, no surgical 
equipment, no power. There is also no hope that Gorazde's 
hellish experience is nearing an end. On the contrary, the 
attacks are increasing. 
  Deadly tank shells are raining down from Ustipraca on both 
banks of the Drina. Infantry attacks against the defense lines 
of Kopaci are supported with fire from howitzers and all other 
artillery weapons. Chetniks are also attacking the defence 
lines of Gotunjak, [place name indistinct] Hill and Gradina. 
They are also launching attacks on the northern side of Gorazde 
from the direction of Metvici, toward the villages of Vrazalice 
and Tvitjak, and the Trovrh peak. 
  The situation, however, is most critical at the approaches 
to 
the town, on the right bank of the Drina. Serbian and 
Montenegrin volunteers are systematically firing at civilian 
facilities. The town is being systematically destroyed with all 
available weapons since 0900 -- street by street, house by 
house. Many houses have been destroyed, many are in flames. It 
is futile to expect anything to change here without an urgent 
intervention by the international community. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8055 </DOCNO>
