<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Villages in Flames </H4>

<F P=102> AU1004141494 Paris AFP in English 1413 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1004141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Zagreb, April 10 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb troops 
besieging the Moslem town of Gorazde on Sunday began crossing 
the Drina river just to the south following a massive artillery 
offensive, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees announced. 
  The soldiers began crossing the river, which had marked the 
front line between warring forces, shortly after 3:00 p.m. (1300 
GMT), the UNHCR spokesman in Zagreb, Peter Kessler said. 
  Half an hour later, shells continued to "pour down" on the 
villages of Bacci and Vinarici to the south of Gorazde, while 
three other villages to the east were in flames, he added. 
  General Michael Rose, commander of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in Bosnia, called off a flight to Brussels from the 
Croatian port of Split and returned rapidly to the Bosnian 
capital Sarajevo, UNPROFOR officials here said. 
  Rose's spokesman here was unable to say whether the sudden 
change in his plans was due to developments in Gorazde. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

