<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Tremendous Relief' Following Strike </H4>

<F P=102> AU1004194994 Paris AFP in English 1940 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1004194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, April 10 (AFP) -- [passage omitted] 
Aid workers said that Serb shelling of Gorazde had ceased after 
the [NATO] air strikes, bringing relief after the assault on the 
town, while civilians had taken advantage of the lull to take 
the wounded to hospital. 
  In Brussels, NATO diplomats said the strikes occurred some 
45 
minutes after UNPROFOR forces were attacked from a position 
occupied by Bosnian Serbs. 
  The Serb military command for Herzegovina, carrying out the 
offensive on Gorazde, said NATO planes had struck Bosnian Serb 
positions in the Preljuca and Goli Vrh region, 12 kilometres 
(seven miles) southwest of the town. [passage omitted] 
  The private Italian television station TG5 said the planes 
left from Aviano in northeast Italy and reported that the attack 
had left casualties, but gave no sources. [passage omitted] 
  A UN High Commissioner for Refugees spokesman in Belgrade, 
Lyndall Sachs, said: "The town (Gorazde) is calm and there is a 
feeling of tremendous relief among the people" after a day of 
panicked fleeing before the Serb offensive. 
  "Now everyone is catching their breath," Eric Stobbaerts, 
Belgrade representative for Medecins sans Frontieres (MSF: 
Doctors Without Borders) said, "and waiting to see what will 
happen tonight." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

