<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN Threatens More Air Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> AU1004201294 Paris AFP in English 2002 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1004201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 10 (AFP) -- The United Nations warned 
Sunday it would order more air strikes against Serb forces 
around the eastern Bosnian town of Gorazde if necessary. 
  Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali "would like to make it 
very clear that he will not hesitate to use airpower again to 
protect UN-designated safe areas," said UN spokeswoman Therese 
Gastaut. Gorazde is one of six such areas in Bosnia. 
  Two U.S. F-16 fighter planes attacked Serb positions near 
Gorazde Sunday, officials in Washington and Brussels said. 
  The air raids were ordered by the top UN official in the 
former Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, in consultation with 
Butrus-Ghali to protect eight UN observers in the Gorazde 
enclave, Gastaut said. 
  U.S. F-16 warplanes carried out two sorties, at 1625 GMT and 
1629 GMT, she said. She characterized the attacks as "close air 
support" rather than air strikes in the traditional sense 
because the objective was to protect the observers and other UN 
staff in Gorazde. 
  On Saturday Butrus-Ghali instructed the UN force in Bosnia 
to 
use all means necessary to force the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw 
to positions they held before their Gorazde offensive began in 
late March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

