<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Muslim Attacks Follow Air Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> LD1104131594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1251 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1104131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, April 11 (TANJUG) -- Following Sunday's 
bombing by the NATO aircraft of Bosnian Serb targets south of 
Gorazde, Bosnian Moslem forces attacked early on Monday Serb 
positions along several major directions, along which they have 
been undertaking offensive actions for days already. 
  Supported by their artillery, Moslems attacked from Bugojno 
in the direction of Srbobran, central Bosnia, while the corridor 
and Serb positions near Brcko and Doboj bore the brunt of Moslem 
attacks in northern Bosnia. 
  Early on Monday Moslem forces delivered a heavy 
mortar-infantry attack 7 km southwest of Brcko on Serb positions 
in the area of Ulice, Lukici and Lipovac, Bosnian Serb military 
sources said. 
  Members of the Bosnian Serb army defending access points to 
Brcko and the corridor linking eastern and western Bosnia and 
the republic of Serb Krajina, responded to the attack and a lull 
followed in that part of the front along the River Sava valley. 
  Moslem units are launching heavy attacks along nearly all 
directions around Doboj, the sources said. 
  Moslem forces on Monday resumed unabated artillery attacks 
on 
the western positions on the Doboj front and its suburbs and 
residential areas. 
  Except for a few observations by U.N. representatives that 
Moslems were undertaking offensive actions in the Doboj region 
and warnings to them not to provoke Serbs, there were no 
stronger reactions by the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) to a 
nearly two-week-long Moslem offensive on Doboj, Bosnian Serb 
sources said. The media attention was in that period focused on 
Gorazde, from which 10,000 Moslem troops mounted a fierce 
offensive and thus provoked the Serb counter-offensive. 
  Serb positions and localities on the right bank of the River 
Bosna, from Zavidovici to Maglaj (south of Doboj), were a target 
of heavy infantry and mortar fire. Serb forces did not have any 
casualties and repulsed a stronger artillery-infantry attack in 
the Trebava front, northeast of Doboj. 
  Moslem forces did not cease attacks on the Srbobran front 
either, from the direction of Bugojno in central Bosnia. 
Attacks were renewed along almost all sectors of the front in 
this area, Bosnian Serb military sources reported on Monday. 
  Since the outset of the all-out Moslem offensive on the 
Bosnian Serb Republic mounted late in March, forces of Bosnian 
Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic have been trying to reopen the 
strategically important road to Jajce and western Bosnia, by 
breaking through Serb lines in the direction of Srbobran. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8083 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu069_i_94035" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-069 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting, Situation Around Gorazde Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Second NATO Air Strike Reported </H4>

<F P=102> LD1104125394 Paris Radio France International in French 1200 
GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Two NATO air raids in two days in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. NATO aircraft have just attacked Serb 
positions again around the Muslim enclave of Gorazde. This news 
has not been officially confirmed yet by the United Nations. 
  Some hours ago, the UN special representative for Bosnia was 
warning that new air strikes were possible in case of threats 
against the safe havens. Yasushi Akashi was speaking in Paris. 
Shortly after the Atlantic Alliance apparently carried out a 
second air strike against the surrounding Serb positions, 
shelling the Muslim enclave of Gorazde. More details with Denis 
Hourdan: 
  [Hourdan] It seems that NATO planes are carrying out new air 
strikes on Serb positions around Gorazde. For the time being UN 
official spokesmen in Sarajevo refuse to confirm the news given 
by a UNHCR [UN High Commissioner for Refugees] civilian who was 
in General Rose's command post in Sarajevo. This UN official 
told us that new raids were under way after this morning's heavy 
shelling of Gorazde. Serbs first targetted Gorazde hospital, 
and then the residence of UN military observers. This latest 
move apparently prompted NATO's latest raid. NATO dispatched 
planes that identified targets. The United Nations refuses to 
confirm that the planes fired, but apparently new air strikes 
took place. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

