<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Tense' Muslim-Serb Talks in Sarajevo Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Tense' Muslim-Serb Talks in Sarajevo Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0904155094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1452 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0904155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 9 Apr (TANJUG) -- A meeting between the 
commanders of the [Bosnian] Serb and Muslim armies, with 
UNPROFOR's [UN Protection Forces] mediation, which began around 
1300 at Sarajevo airport, is still under way this afternoon, and 
could go on for several hours. 
  As TANJUG's correspondent has learned, the talks are 
difficult and tense, and it is completely uncertain whether the 
standpoints of the two sides will come closer, and whether a 
cease-fire agreement will be signed. 
  The commander of the main headquarters of the Srpska 
republic 
army, Lt. Col. Gen. Ratko Mladic; the commander of the Muslim 
forces, Gen. Rasim Delic; and the UNPROFOR commander for former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Gen. Michael Rose, are holding talks behind 
closed doors. 
  Today's meeting is a result of efforts made yesterday by Gen 
Rose to get both commanders to the negotiating table. However, 
their different standpoints on the peace agreement have not been 
reconciled and it could be said that bridging this gap will be 
the central topic of the talks. 
  TANJUG has learned from reliable sources that the Muslim 
side 
arrived at the meeting with a 14-day cease-fire offer, insisting 
that Gorazde be the main topic. 
  However, as Gen. Mladic pointed out at the meeting, the Serb 
side does not want to discuss partial and short-term solutions, 
but it has offered talks on an overall and unconditional truce 
along all demarcation lines in former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Thus the Serb side is not prepared to discuss any particular 
front outside the context of the overall situation; this is 
contrary to the standpoints of the Muslim forces' command, which 
is trying to give top priority, in achieving a truce, to those 
battlefields where which the situation is developing in a way 
completely out of keeping with its wishes and aims. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
