<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protests `Shocking Precedent' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Protests `Shocking Precedent' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1104102194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0910 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knin, 11 Apr (TANJUG) -- The people and the 
leadership of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK] are deeply 
indignant over the shocking precedent set by NATO forces, under 
the auspices of the [UN] Security Council, by the bombing of 
Serb positions in the Srpska republic, with no prior notice and 
no good reason, RSK President Milan Martic said today. 
  "We sharply protest this insolent action which has 
undermined 
all efforts to end the crisis in the territory of former 
Yugoslavia by peaceful means," a statement stresses and adds 
that NATO's attack on the Srpska republic has further shaken the 
Serb people's confidence in the international community, which 
was at its lowest level anyway, due to the international 
community's partisan and biased attitude in the past. 
  "With this act of aggression the international community has 
declared war on the Serb people, thus trying to force it -- 
under the threat of NATO's war machinery -- to accept solutions 
which are in the interest of the other two warring sides and 
detrimental to the Serb people," the RSK president warns. 
  The statement goes on to say: 
  ``The RSK people and leadership again express their full 
support for our brothers in the Srpska republic and their 
efforts to defend their freedom won in blood. 
  ``Those who committed this thoughtless act will bear the 
blame for all the possible consequences of the bombing of the 
Srpska republic on the further course of the peace process in 
the territory of former Yugoslavia. 
  "At the same time, we warn all the relevant international 
factors that the RSK will not tolerate any attempts to solve its 
future political status through pressure and threats, regardless 
from which side they come." 

</TEXT>

