<H3> <TI>   Granic, Greek Officials Discuss Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Granic, Greek Officials Discuss Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0804135394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0804135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs -- ahead of his scheduled visit to 
Greece -- today received Pavlos Apostolidis, director of the 
Greek Foreign Ministry Political Relations Office, and the 
Zagreb-based head of the EC monitoring mission, Greek Ambassador 
Constantin Yerocostopoulos [names as heard]. The meeting was 
also attended by Croatian Deputy Foreign Minister Ivo Sanader. 
  Granic informed his guests about the course of the 
implementation of the cease-fire agreement between the Croatian 
authorities and the local Serbs living in UN protected areas, 
and announced that negotiations would resume next week. 
Speaking about the peace process in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Granic 
stressed the importance of the establishment of a total 
cease-fire in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the resumption of peace 
talks. He said that the Serb side should immediately join the 
talks and that the European Union should be more efficient. 
  Granic and Sanader also spoke about preparations for the 
reconstruction of Croatia, for which it is necessary to obtain 
economic aid, particularly from the European Union, as Croatia 
is a European country and wishes to join its political and 
economic trends. 
  Granic and his guests agreed that relations between Croatia 
and Greece are good, and that the visit by the Croatian foreign 
minister to Greece will contribute to their future bilateral 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

