<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK: Solution Only Possible Within Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RSK: Solution Only Possible Within Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1004192994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1910 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1004192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Knin, April 10 (TANJUG) -- Republic of Serb Krajina 
(RSK) President Milan Martic said Sunday that the RSK Parliament 
maintained that a political solution to the RSK should only be 
sought within the conference on the former Yugoslavia. 
  Martic conferred in Knin with Deputy Co-chairman of the 
Conference on the Former Yugoslavia Kai Eide and Russian 
Ambassador in Zagreb Leonid Kerestedzhiants at a preliminary 
meeting ahead of the second-round RSK-Krajina talks, opened in 
March. 
  The republic of Serb Krajina was proclaimed in 1991 by the 
local Serbs in their ancestral lands within Croatia's 
Communist-era arbitrary borders, in response to Croatia's 
violent secession from the former Yugoslav Federation and its 
attempt to downgrade the local Serbs' status to that of a 
national minority. Krajina became a U.N.-Protected Area in 
March 1992. 
  In two referendums so far, the RSK Serbs have voted against 
their return to Zagreb's jurisdiction. 
  On March 30, RSK and Croatian representatives signed a 
ceasefire agreement in the Russian embassy in Zagreb. The 
agreement took effect on April 4. 
  The RSK Parliament believes that the second phase of the 
talks, which is to include economic, humanitarian and political 
issues, could be held in any Russian embassy, except the one in 
Zagreb, said Martic. 
  After the talks, Martic assessed them as very useful and 
voiced his satisfaction with the degree of Eide's and 
Kerestedzhiants's understanding for RSK stands. He added that 
only an impartial stand towards the relations in the area could 
bring about solutions acceptable to all. 
  Eide, for his part, said that the ceasefire agreement was 
reached and observed by both sides, adding that the 
international community was very well prepared for the 
second-round RSK-Croatia talks which should open as soon as 
possible. 
  The international community platform on RSK-Croatia 
humanitarian relations gives priority to the re-opening of 
traffic and communications. Also to be discussed in terms of 
priority are: Industrial cooperation, cooperation in the field 
of energy and water supplies, trade and agriculture and lastly, 
social welfare policy and humanitarian relations issues. 
  It has been confirmed that the RSK is soon to submit a list 
of its own priorities. 
  Eide said that if both sides showed good will and readiness 
to cooperate, the way they did with the ceasefire agreement, the 
results would soon follow. 
  Kerestedzhiants said that it was all up to Knin and Zagreb, 
adding that reaching a political settlement would also depend on 
both sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-8110 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu069_k_94007" </HT>


